<subSubSection id="D5CD7AD20424FFB7FC9AFB82FBBF9431" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="96" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph id="9D6829590424FFB6FC9AFB82FAC49031" blockId="0.[839,1468,1118,1641]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FC9AFB82FB6C9103" bold="true" box="[839,1177,1118,1143]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Description and delimitation</emphasis>
. See 
<bibRefCitation id="F94654A80424FFB6FB01FB82FA7C9103" author="Hendel, F." box="[1244,1417,1118,1142]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" refId="ref4315" refString="Hendel, F. 1914 a. Diptera, Fam. Muscaridae, Subfam. Platystominae. Genera Insectorum 157: 179 pp., 15 pls." type="book" year="1914">Hendel (1914a)</bibRefCitation>
and further notes by 
<bibRefCitation id="F94654A80424FFB6FC2DFBA0FB2891E6" author="McAlpine, D. K." box="[1008,1245,1147,1172]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" pagination="113 - 199" refId="ref4548" refString="McAlpine, D. K. 2001. Review of the Australasian genera of signal flies (Diptera: Platystomatidae). Records of the Australian Museum 53 (2): 113 - 199. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1975.53.2001.1327" type="journal article" year="2001">McAlpine (2001: 152)</bibRefCitation>
. The genus should be identifiable from the key to platystomatid genera in 
<bibRefCitation id="F94654A80424FFB6FA8CFB45FC0D91BB" author="McAlpine, D. K." pageId="0" pageNumber="95" pagination="113 - 199" refId="ref4548" refString="McAlpine, D. K. 2001. Review of the Australasian genera of signal flies (Diptera: Platystomatidae). Records of the Australian Museum 53 (2): 113 - 199. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1975.53.2001.1327" type="journal article" year="2001">McAlpine (2001: 121–130)</bibRefCitation>
. The species superficially resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FC9AFB0FFB909199" authority="Hendel" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1912" box="[839,1125,1235,1260]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Plagiostenopterina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FC9AFB0FFBE7919E" box="[839,1042,1235,1259]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Plagiostenopterina</emphasis>
Hendel
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FB44FB0FFA939199" authority="Bigot" authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1860" box="[1177,1382,1235,1260]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Elassogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FB44FB0FFAD7919E" box="[1177,1314,1235,1259]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Elassogaster</emphasis>
Bigot
</taxonomicName>
, but the males have a single hollow terminal filament on the aedeagus, while apparently all related genera have two (rarely three) terminal filaments, each with apical gonopore.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D6829590424FFB6FCB8FA95FADF931C" blockId="0.[839,1468,1118,1641]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">
<bibRefCitation id="F94654A80424FFB6FCB8FA95FBBC9014" author="Evenhuis, N. L." box="[869,1097,1353,1377]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" pagination="482 - 497" refId="ref4258" refString="Evenhuis, N. L. 1989. 64. Family Platystomatidae. In Catalog of the Diptera of the Australasian and Oceanian Regions, ed. N. L. Evenhuis. Bishop Museum Special Publication 86: 482 - 497. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 49897" type="journal article" year="1989">Evenhuis (1989:493)</bibRefCitation>
listed six Australasian species of 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FC9AFABBFC1B900B" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[839,1006,1383,1406]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FC9AFABBFC1B900B" box="[839,1006,1383,1406]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Microepicausta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. His two included Australian species, 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FA43FABBFC0590E9" authority="Hendel" authorityName="Hendel, Bronte" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FA43FABBFC6C90EE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">M. gracilis</emphasis>
Hendel
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FBF7FA58FAAD90E9" authority="(Malloch)" baseAuthorityName="Malloch" baseAuthorityYear="1928" box="[1066,1368,1412,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="terraereginae">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FBF7FA58FB1690EE" box="[1066,1251,1412,1435]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">M. terraereginae</emphasis>
(Malloch)
</taxonomicName>
are now considered to be synonyms, and 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FB71FA7EFA8B90CC" authority="(Malloch)" baseAuthorityName="Malloch" box="[1196,1406,1441,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="evitta">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FB71FA7EFAF990CC" box="[1196,1292,1442,1465]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">M. evitta</emphasis>
(Malloch)
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectingCountry id="E5C069C90424FFB6FCADFA62FBA890A3" box="[880,1117,1470,1494]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Bismarck Archipelago</collectingCountry>
is now placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0424FFB6FA4EFA63FBF59081" authority="McAlpine, 2001" authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="2001" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Par" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0424FFB6FA4EFA63FA4F90A3" box="[1427,1466,1471,1494]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Par</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="F94654A80424FFB6FC9AFA00FBF59081" author="McAlpine, D. K." box="[839,1024,1500,1524]" pageId="0" pageNumber="95" pagination="113 - 199" refId="ref4548" refString="McAlpine, D. K. 2001. Review of the Australasian genera of signal flies (Diptera: Platystomatidae). Records of the Australian Museum 53 (2): 113 - 199. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1975.53.2001.1327" type="journal article" year="2001">McAlpine, 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The known Australian species, treated below, live on the northern and eastern Australian coasts as far south as Tasmania, with one record for coastal South Australia. Other species that I have seen range from West New 
<collectingCountry id="E5C069C90424FFB6FAB2F9E8FA4E9339" box="[1391,1467,1588,1612]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="0" pageNumber="95">Guinea</collectingCountry>
to New Ireland and the Solomon Archipelago.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D6829590425FFB7FFA4FF46FBBF9431" blockId="1.[121,749,154,295]" lastBlockId="1.[794,1422,154,325]" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FFA4FF46FF2595C7" bold="true" box="[121,208,154,178]" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Habitat</emphasis>
. In temperate eastern 
<collectingCountry id="E5C069C90425FFB7FE6EFF46FDE295C7" box="[435,535,154,178]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Australia</collectingCountry>
, the two represented species, 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0425FFB7FF06FF64FDB195BA" authority="Hendel" authorityName="Hendel, Bronte" authorityYear="1914" box="[219,580,183,207]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FF06FF64FE1F95BA" box="[219,490,183,207]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Microepicausta gracilis</emphasis>
Hendel
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0425FFB7FD5CFF64FD1895BA" authority="Mcalpine, 2019" authorityName="Mcalpine" authorityYear="2019" box="[641,749,183,207]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wirthi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FD5CFF64FD1895BA" box="[641,749,183,207]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">M. wirthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B49048300425FFB7FFA4FF09FF389599" box="[121,205,213,236]" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are restricted to areas near the coast with a sandy substrate. 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0425FFB7FF37FF2EFE29947F" authorityName="Mcalpine" authorityYear="2019" box="[234,476,242,266]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wirthi">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FF37FF2EFE29947F" box="[234,476,242,266]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Microepicausta wirthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is particularly restricted to the immediate vicinity of the shoreline on dunes and the landward borders of beaches. The flies have commonly been found on the native grass 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0425FFB7FBE7FF6BFB0595BA" box="[1082,1264,183,207]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Spinifex" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericeus">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FBE7FF6BFB0595BA" box="[1082,1264,183,207]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Spinifex sericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is one of the most conspicuous plants in this habitat. Though the larvae of 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0425FFB7FCA2FF2EFBD0947C" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[895,1061,242,265]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FCA2FF2EFBD0947C" box="[895,1061,242,265]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">Microepicausta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are not yet known, I suspect that those of 
<taxonomicName id="5AD752DA0425FFB7FC7FFECCFBF19452" authorityName="Mcalpine" authorityYear="2019" box="[930,1028,271,295]" class="Insecta" family="Platystomatidae" genus="Microepicausta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wirthi">
<emphasis id="AFA3F54B0425FFB7FC7FFECCFBF19452" box="[930,1028,271,295]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="96">M. wirthi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be associated with the rhizomes or root systems of this plant.
</paragraph>
